{"title_page": "Ryan Babel", "text_new": "{{short description|Dutch footballer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Ryan Babel\n| image = Ryan-babel-6.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption =\n| fullname = Ryan Guno Babel<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1034294 |title=Updated squad lists for 2018/19 Premier League |publisher=Premier League |date=1 February 2019 |accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|12|19|df=y}}<ref name=\"Hugman2010-11\">{{cite book |editor-first=Barry J. |editor-last=Hugman |title=The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2010\u201311 |year=2010 |publisher=Mainstream Publishing |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-1-84596-601-0 |page=29}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Amsterdam]], Netherlands\n| height = 1.85 m<ref name=\"1889 Hoffenheim profile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.achtzehn99.de/spielerportrait-profis-en-2/3129/?lang=new |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120810000226/http://www.achtzehn99.de/spielerportrait-profis/profis/3129 |archivedate=10 August 2012 |title=1889 Hoffenheim Official profile |publisher=1889 Hoffenheim |accessdate=29 January 2011}}</ref>\n| currentclub = [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] (on loan from [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]])\n| clubnumber = 49\n| position = [[Forward (association football)#Winger|Winger]]\n| youthyears1 = 1992\u20131994\n| youthclubs1 = SV Diemen\n| youthyears2 = 1994\u20131997\n| youthclubs2 = ASV Fortius\n| youthyears3 = 1997\u20132004\n| youthclubs3 = [[Ajax Youth Academy|Ajax]]\n| years1 = 2004\u20132007\n| clubs1 = [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]\n| caps1 = 73\n| goals1 = 14\n| years2 = 2007\u20132011\n| clubs2 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| caps2 = 91\n| goals2 = 12\n| years3 = 2011\u20132012\n| clubs3 = [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|1899 Hoffenheim]]\n| caps3 = 46\n| goals3 = 5\n| years4 = 2012\u20132013\n| clubs4 = [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]\n| caps4 = 16\n| goals4 = 4\n| years5 = 2013\u20132015\n| clubs5 = [[Kas\u0131mpa\u015fa S.K.|Kas\u0131mpa\u015fa]]\n| caps5 = 58\n| goals5 = 14\n| years6 = 2015\u20132016\n| clubs6 = [[Al Ain FC|Al Ain]]\n| caps6 = 8\n| goals6 = 1\n| years7 = 2016\n| clubs7 = [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]]\n| caps7 = 11\n| goals7 = 4\n| years8 = 2017\u20132019\n| clubs8 = [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]]\n| caps8 = 62\n| goals8 = 22\n| years9 = 2019\n| clubs9 = [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]\n| caps9 = 16\n| goals9 = 5\n| years10 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs10 = [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]]\n| caps10 = 15\n| goals10 = 5\n| years11 = 2020\n| clubs11 = \u2192 [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] (loan)\n| caps11 = 3\n| goals11 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2002\u20132003\n| nationalteam1 = [[Netherlands national under-17 football team|Netherlands U17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 2003\u20132004\n| nationalteam2 = [[Netherlands national under-19 football team|Netherlands U19]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 6\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 2004\u20132005\n| nationalteam3 = Netherlands U20\n| nationalcaps3 = 4\n| nationalgoals3 = 2\n| nationalyears4 = 2005\u20132007\n| nationalteam4 = [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands U21]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 5\n| nationalgoals4 = 2\n| nationalyears5 = 2008\n| nationalteam5 = [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands U23]]\n| nationalcaps5 = 5\n| nationalgoals5 = 2\n| nationalyears6 = 2005\u2013\n| nationalteam6 = [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]]\n| nationalcaps6 = 63\n| nationalgoals6 = 10\n| club-update = 10 February 2020\n| nationalteam-update = 10 October 2019\n| medaltemplates = {{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{fb|NED}}}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 South Africa]]|}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[UEFA Nations League]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals|2019 Portugal]]|}}\n{{Medal|Comp|[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]|}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2007 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2007 Netherlands]]|}}\n}}\n'''Ryan Guno Babel''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8r\u0251j\u0250n \u02c8ba\u02d0b\u0259l}}; born 19 December 1986)<ref name=\"LFC profile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/team/first-team/player/19-ryan-babel |title=Liverpool F.C. Official profile |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |accessdate=16 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128060918/http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/team/first-team/player/19-ryan-babel |archivedate=28 January 2010}}</ref> is a Dutch professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[AFC Ajax]], on loan from [[S\u00fcper Lig]] club [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]], and the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands national team]]. He can play as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]] or [[Winger (association football)|left winger]].\n\nBabel began his career at Ajax in 1998, working his way up through the youth team and into the senior squad. He played three seasons for the first team before he was transferred to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in mid-2007, where under three successive managers he failed to secure a regular first team position. Babel was sold to [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim]] in January 2011, for a sum around half of that which Liverpool paid for him. His time at Hoffenheim was marred with disciplinary problems with three managers at the club. In the summer of 2012, Babel bought out the remaining final year of his contract, making him a free agent, and re-signed a one-year contract with Ajax. After this season, Babel went on to sign with Turkish club [[Kas\u0131mpa\u015fa S.K.|Kas\u0131mpa\u015fa]] on 21 June 2013. Babel often was linked to a return to the Premier League during his time in Turkey, before ending rumours by signing for UAE side [[Al Ain FC]] in July 2015.\n\nIn January 2020, Babel moved to Ajax on loan for the rest of the season, joining the club for the third time in his career.\n\nBabel has been part of the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands national team]] since 2005, and has represented his country at all youth team levels. He played in two World Cups, 2006 and 2010, reaching the final of the latter.\n\nFrom late March 2020, he has been a regular on Tory Lanez' Quarantine Radio with some very questionable comments.\n\n==Early career==\nBabel was born in [[Amsterdam]].<ref name=\"Hugman2010-11\"/> Inspired by the local footballing talent, including [[Ruud Gullit]] and [[Frank Rijkaard]], Babel played for nearby youth-teams S.V Diemen, then Fortius.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.babelofficial.com/en/biography.asp |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529051821/http://www.babelofficial.com/en/biography.asp |archivedate=29 May 2010 |title=Biography |publisher=Babelofficial.com |accessdate=9 February 2009}}</ref> In 1997, he attended a youth selection day with [[AFC Ajax]]. He made it through the first selection round, but failed to progress any further.<ref name=biography>{{cite web |title=Biography |publisher=ryanbabel.nl |url=http://www.ryanbabel.nl/ryanbabel/biografie.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823165051/http://www.ryanbabel.nl/ryanbabel/biografie.html |archivedate=23 August 2012 |accessdate=23 June 2007 |language=Dutch}}</ref> However, the next year Ajax accepted him and he played the 1999\u20132000 season for their D1 team.<ref name=biography/> After having graduated through the C1, B1 and A1 teams, Babel signed his first professional contract in January 2004.<ref name=biography/>\n\n==Club career==\n===Ajax===\nPlaying as a [[Forward (association football)|striker]], on 1 February 2004, just one and a half months after his 17th birthday, Babel made his first-team debut in Ajax's 4\u20130 home win over [[ADO Den Haag]] in the [[Eredivisie]].<ref name=ARCHIVES>{{cite web |url=http://english.ajax.nl/web/show/id=154814/contentid=61694 |title=Extension for Ryan Babel |publisher=AFC Ajax |date=2 February 2007 |accessdate=7 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313203650/http://english.ajax.nl/web/show/id%3D154814/contentid%3D61694 |archivedate=13 March 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Ajax went on to win the Dutch league title, but Babel didn't feature again that season. Nine months later, on 20 November 2004 Babel scored his first senior goal against [[De Graafschap]] in a 5\u20130 victory.<ref name=fifa>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/news/newsid=26825.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222165032/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/news/newsid=26825.html |archivedate=22 February 2014 |title=Babel rewarding Van Basten's faith |publisher=FIFA |date=16 January 2006 |accessdate=11 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2005, Babel signed a new contract with Ajax. He started the new season by scoring the winning goal in Ajax's 2\u20131 defeat of [[PSV Eindhoven]] in the [[Johan Cruyff Shield]]. Babel scored in both legs of the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] third qualifying round against [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]] as Ajax made it to the group stage. 2005\u201306 was a tougher season for Babel in general though as he managed only two league goals. He did however continue to feature for the national team, and scored his second goal against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in November. At the end of the season, Babel came on as a second-half [[substitute (association football)|substitute]] in Ajax's 2\u20131 victory over PSV in the [[KNVB Cup]] final.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nBabel marked the start of 2006\u201307 with another Johan Cruyff Shield medal, as Ajax defeated PSV 3\u20131. Babel was linked with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and [[Newcastle United]] during the January transfer window of the [[2007 in football (soccer)|2006\u201307 season]] but no move materialised.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sport.independent.co.uk/football/news/article2137748.ece |title=West Ham in for Ljungberg as Arsenal line up Dutch star |last=Burt |first=Jason |newspaper=The Independent |date=9 January 2007 |accessdate=7 May 2007 |location=London |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070714071255/http://sport.independent.co.uk/football/news/article2137748.ece |archivedate=14 July 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11678/2402772/babel-catching-magpies-eye |title=Babel catching Magpies' eye |last=van Leeuwen |first=Gerrit |publisher=Sky Sports |date=18 January 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> Amidst the transfer speculation, Babel agreed to a new three-year deal with Ajax on 2 February 2007.<ref name=\"ARCHIVES\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://home.skysports.com/list.aspx?hlid=472023&CPID=9&clid=3&lid=&title=Ajax+star+wowed+by+Wenger |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070703085837/http://home.skysports.com/list.aspx?hlid=472023&CPID=9&clid=3&lid=&title=Ajax+star+wowed+by+Wenger |archivedate=3 July 2007 |title=Ajax star wowed by Wenger |publisher=Sky Sports |date=14 June 2007}}</ref> In May, Babel got another Dutch Cup winners medal as Ajax successfully defended the title. The match against AZ went to a penalty shoot-out, but Babel was substituted off after 120 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.knvb.nl/clubs/knvbbeker/archief/knvb_beker_nieuw/ajax_wint_beker_na_thriller |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204033937/http://www.knvb.nl/clubs/knvbbeker/archief/knvb_beker_nieuw/ajax_wint_beker_na_thriller |archivedate=4 February 2010 |title=Ajax win cup in thriller |publisher=Royal Dutch Football Association |date=6 May 2007 |accessdate=11 July 2007 |language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\n===Liverpool===\nOn 10 July 2007, it was reported that [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] had made a [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]14&nbsp;million offer to the Amsterdam club.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/6285040.stm |title=Liverpool make improved Babel bid |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 July 2007 |accessdate=16 September 2008}}</ref> On 12 July it was reported that Liverpool and Ajax had agreed a fee in the region of \u00a311.5&nbsp;million, and later Liverpool confirmed that Babel would sign a five-year contract on 13 July.<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Eaton |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/babel-to-sign-for-reds-today |title=Babel set to sign on Friday |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |date=23 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826160941/http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/babel-to-sign-for-reds-today |archivedate=26 August 2014}}</ref> He was unveiled on 13 July with [[Yossi Benayoun]]. Babel was handed the number 19 shirt. He made his debut on 17 July against [[Werder Bremen]] in a friendly. He was due to play in the first round of the [[Barclays Asia Trophy 2007]] but had a delay in the granting of international clearance. This was sorted out in time for the final against Portsmouth.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11669/2621711/reds-reach-asia-trophy-final |title=Reds reach Asia Trophy final |publisher=Sky Sports |date=24 July 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe made his [[Premier League]] debut in the 2007\u201308 Premier League curtain raiser against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] away after coming on off the bench. A week later he made his [[Anfield]] debut, coming off the bench against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]. On 1 September Babel scored his first goal for Liverpool against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6963702.stm |title=Liverpool 6\u20130 Derby |publisher=BBC Sport |date=1 September 2007 |accessdate=4 September 2009 |first=Chris |last=Bevan}}</ref> Babel scored his first Champions League goal for Liverpool on 6 November against [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.]] after coming on as a substitute. He netted twice in the game and almost completed a hat-trick, with a header from a [[Harry Kewell]] cross, but was denied by the crossbar.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7076592.stm |title=Liverpool 8\u20130 Besiktas |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 November 2007 |accessdate=4 September 2009 |first=Mandeep |last=Sanghera}}</ref> Babel scored the fourth and last goal in Liverpool's [[2007\u201308 UEFA Champions League group stage]] match against [[Olympique de Marseille]], which they needed to win.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7136346.stm |title=Marseille 0\u20134 Liverpool |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 December 2007 |accessdate=4 September 2009 |first=John |last=Sinnott}}</ref> He came off the bench in the second leg of the quarter final against Arsenal in the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] and won a penalty and scored a goal, with Liverpool winning the game 4\u20132 (5\u20133 on aggregate).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7332209.stm |title=Liverpool 4\u20132 Arsenal (agg 5\u20133) |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 April 2008 |accessdate=4 September 2009 |first=Andrew |last=McKenzie}}</ref> He also came on as a substitute against Chelsea in the semi-final and despite scoring a goal, Liverpool lost 3\u20132 in extra time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7368736.stm |title=Chelsea 3\u20132 Liverpool (4\u20133) |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 April 2008 |accessdate=4 September 2009 |first=Sam |last=Lyon}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ryan Babel 2010.jpg|thumb|left|Babel before Jamie Carragher's testimonial match in 2010]]\n\nFormer Liverpool and [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] player [[Kenny Dalglish]] has said that Babel has the ability to terrorise defenders in the Premier League with his pace and trickery with the ball.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/kenny-babel-is-terrifying |title=Kenny: Babel Is Terrifying |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |date=23 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826114541/http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/kenny-babel-is-terrifying |archivedate=26 August 2014}}</ref> On 13 September 2008, Babel came off the bench to score the winner for Liverpool in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Manchester United]], his first goal of the [[Premier League 2008-09|2008\u201309 season]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/babel-propels-liverpool-to-win-over-manchester-united-1.719115 |title=Babel propels Liverpool to win over Manchester United |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=13 September 2008 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> Babel scored his second goal of the season in Liverpool's 5\u20131 victory over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on 28 December 2008.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7788422.stm |title=Newcastle 1\u20135 Liverpool |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 December 2008 |accessdate=4 September 2009 |first=Phil |last=McNulty}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 September 2009, against West Ham, Babel came off the bench for Dirk Kuyt. At this stage the score was 2\u20132. Babel picked up the ball and did well to beat the full-back and sent in a delightful cross for [[Fernando Torres]] to head home the winner. Babel, who has been criticised in the past for his work rate and attitude, earned praise for his efforts in the West Ham game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/news/drilldown/N165837090920-0012.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091126140048/http://www.liverpoolfc.tv/news/drilldown/N165837090920-0012.htm |archivedate=26 November 2009 |title=Torres: My goal debt to Babel |first=Steve |last=Hunter |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |date=20 September 2009 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\nOn 27 September 2009, Babel scored two goals against [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] coming off the bench for Fernando Torres to round up a match which ended 6\u20131 for Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/8270616.stm |title=Liverpool 6\u20131 Hull |date=26 September 2009 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=10 November 2009 |first=Jonathan |last=Stevenson}}</ref> On 4 November 2009, Babel scored the opening goal against [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] in a Champions League game, a strike from 25 yards in a 1\u20131 draw. Former Liverpool player [[Alan Hansen]] called upon Babel to play like he did against Lyon, as he still possessed the ability to be a 'top player'.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/8338788.stm |title=Lyon 1\u20131 Liverpool |date=4 November 2009 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=10 November 2009 |first=Mandeep |last=Sanghera}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 January 2010, it was reported that Liverpool rejected an \u00a38&nbsp;million offer from [[Birmingham City F.C|Birmingham City]] for Babel.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/liverpool/8443286.stm |title=Birmingham's \u00a38m bid for Liverpool's Ryan Babel denied |date=6 January 2010 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=6 January 2010}}</ref> Babel was then disciplined by manager Benitez, over stating on his Twitter page that he had been dropped for the game against [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]], and was fined two weeks wages of \u00a3120,000. He was frequently linked with a move away from Anfield but Rafael Benitez stated his desire for Babel to stay. On 15 March 2010 he scored against [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] in a 4\u20131 win. On 1 April 2010, he was [[sent off]] for the first time in his Liverpool career in the 30th minute of the first leg of the [[Europa League]] quarter-final against [[S.L. Benfica]] after an altercation with [[Luis\u00e3o]]. He scored in Liverpool's 4\u20130 win over [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] at Turf Moor, subsequently relegating Burnley to the Championship.\nOn 19 August 2010, Babel scored the winner against [[Trabzonspor]] in the [[Europa League]] qualifier first leg, it was his first game of the 2010\u201311 season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/8924283.stm |title=Liverpool 1 \u2013 0 Trabzonspor |date=19 August 2010 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=19 August 2010 |first=Mandeep |last=Sanghera}}</ref> He started his first match in the Premier League at [[Anfield]] against Aston Villa and scored his first goal in the Premier League with a right-footed volley that beat former Liverpool goalkeeper [[Brad Friedel]].{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nBabel gained further notoriety amongst fans when, on [[Transfer window|transfer deadline day]] 31 August 2010, it was reported that the player was travelling by helicopter between Liverpool and an unspecified London location as possible transfer talks with [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] were ongoing, and there was speculation about his true destination.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2010/08/31/2097031/ryan-babel-reveals-on-twitter-im-going-nowhere-after |title=Ryan Babel reveals on Twitter 'I'm going nowhere' after Liverpool accept Tottenham's \u00a35m offer |publisher=Goal.com |date=31 August 2010 |accessdate=2 September 2012}}</ref> No transfer actually occurred and the helicopter story may be apocryphal, but the image stuck and the term \"Babelcopter\" became a metaphor for players with an uncertain destination on future transfer deadline days, with the player himself promoting the use of the [[hashtag]] #BabelCopter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anchorfan.com/image/babelcopter-takes-off-again-with-ryan-babel-reckons-adam-may-be-on-his-way-59191.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130831054542/http://www.anchorfan.com/image/babelcopter-takes-off-again-with-ryan-babel-reckons-adam-may-be-on-his-way-59191.html |archivedate=31 August 2013 |title='BabelCopter' takes off again, and Ryan Babel reckons Adam may be on h |publisher=Anchorfan |accessdate=2 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nOne of the first Premier League players to use Twitter to communicate with fans, in January 2011, Babel posted a [[photoshop]]ped image on Twitter of referee [[Howard Webb]] in a [[Manchester United]] shirt following Liverpool's 1\u20130 defeat to United in the [[2010\u201311 FA Cup|FA Cup]]. He was subsequently charged by [[The Football Association|the F.A.]] with improper conduct and fined \u00a310,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/863846/fa-charges-ryan-babel-for-webb-based-photo-joke?cc=5739 |title=FA charges Babel for Webb tweet |date=10 January 2011 |website=ESPN Soccernet |accessdate=10 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 January, Liverpool agreed a fee believed to be in the region of \u00a37&nbsp;million for Babel from [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/liverpool/8267227/Liverpool-accept-Hoffenheim-bid-for-unsettled-winger-Ryan-Babel.html|title=Liverpool accept Hoffenheim bid for unsettled winger Ryan Babel|date=18 January 2011|website=The Telegraph|accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref> On 24 January, [[Kenny Dalglish]] said that Babel would be staying at Liverpool,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2011/01/24/2320776/kenny-dalglish-confirms-ryan-babel-is-staying-at-liverpool |title=Kenny Dalglish confirm Ryan Babel is staying at Liverpool |date=24 January 2011 |website=Goal.com |accessdate=24 January 2011}}</ref> but the next day Babel flew to Germany to finalise the deal to sign with Hoffenheim.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/70077.html|title=Hoffenheim complete Ryan Babel transfer|website=ESPN.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===1899 Hoffenheim===\nOn 25 January 2011, it was confirmed that Babel had left Liverpool to join German side TSG 1899 Hoffenheim for a reported fee of \u00a38 million, signing a two-and-a-half-year deal.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/liverpool/8281942/Ryan-Babel-leaves-Liverpool-for-Hoffenheim-two-and-a-half-year-contract.html |title=Ryan Babel leaves Liverpool for Hoffenheim two-and-a-half-year contract |date=25 January 2011 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=25 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nHis first competitive match was on 26 January 2011 in the [[DFB-Pokal|DFB Cup]] quarter final match against [[FC Energie Cottbus]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/gamecast/statistics/id/311815/statistics.html |title=Energie Cottbus 1 \u2013 0 TSG Hoffenheim |date=26 January 2011 |website=ESPN Soccernet |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> He is well known for his 'left little finger out' celebration, in support of disadvantaged youths in Amsterdam.\nOn 9 April 2011, Babel scored his first goal for Hoffenheim, in a 3\u20132 loss to [[SC Freiburg]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bundesliga.de/de/liga/matches/2010/spieltag-29/124995/sc-freiburg-vs-1899-hoffenheim/spielbericht.php |title=Bundesliga \u2013 official website |publisher=Bundesliga |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\nIn the 2011\u201312 Bundesliga season, Babel netted his first league goal of the season on 20 August 2011 against [[FC Augsburg|Augsburg]] in a 2\u20130 away win. On 10 September 2011, he scored his first brace for 1899 Hoffenheim in a 4\u20130 win against [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]] and scored again in the next game on 17 September in a 3\u20131 win over [[VfL Wolfsburg]].{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nAfter playing for Hoffenheim for 18 months, scoring six goals in 51 matches, he was released by the club on 31 August 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12691/8036433/Hoffenheim-release-Babel |title=Hoffenheim release Babel |last=Zocher |first=Thomas |publisher=Sky Sports |date=31 August 2012 |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Ajax===\nAfter personally buying off the remaining year of his contract with Hoffenheim, he returned to his old club Ajax on a one-year deal. Wearing shirt number 49, the same number he wore when he made his first ever appearance for the first team at [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], he made his debut with Ajax for the 2012\u201313 season on 15 September 2012, in a regular season match against [[RKC Waalwijk]]. He came on as a substitute for [[Derk Boerrigter]] in the second half, assisting [[Jody Lukoki]] on the second goal in the 2\u20130 home win for the [[Amsterdam]] side.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/08/31/soccer-dutch-babel-idINL4E8JV7HG20120831 |title=Soccer-Babel agrees one-year deal with Ajax |agency=Reuters |date=9 February 2009 |accessdate=2 September 2012}}</ref> He scored his first goal since returning to Ajax in a match against ADO Den Haag on 23 September 2012.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nStruggling with a slight injury midway through the season, Babel managed to play a total of 16 league matches for Ajax, scoring four goals in total in the [[Eredivisie]]. He also made four appearances in the [[2012\u201313 UEFA Champions League]], as well as two more appearances in the [[2012\u201313 KNVB Cup]], where he scored the second goal in the '15-minute of the second round fixture against [[FC Utrecht]], with the match ending 3\u20130 for the Amsterdam side prior to his injury. He would return to action after being sidelined to help his side secure their 3rd consecutive national title and 32nd overall.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n[[File:Ryan Babel 2018 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Ryan Babel playing for Besiktas in 2018.]]\n\n===Kas\u0131mpa\u015fa===\nOpting not to extend his contract with Ajax in order to make way for the next generation,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.voetbalzone.nl/doc.asp?uid=190237 |title=Babel en Malki voor drie jaar naar ambitieus Kasimpasa |publisher=Voetbalzone |date=20 June 2013 |accessdate=12 February 2014 |language=Dutch}}</ref> Babel decided to join Turkish side [[Kas\u0131mpa\u015fa S.K.|Kas\u0131mpa\u015fa]] where former Ajax player [[Shota Arveladze]] was the current manager. He was joined in Turkey by fellow Amsterdam born defender [[Ryan Donk]] who made the transfer from Belgian side [[Club Brugge]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/242146/Kasimpasa-slaat-slag-met-binnenhalen-Babel-en-Donk.htm |title=Kasimpasa slaat slag met binnenhalen Babel en Donk |publisher=Voetbal International |date=5 June 2013 |accessdate=8 June 2013 |language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\n===Al Ain===\nBabel signed a contract with [[UAE Arabian Gulf League]] champions [[Al Ain FC|Al Ain]] to replace the outgoing [[Miroslav Stoch]]. He signed the contract after passing a medical test on 2 July 2015. In December 2015, Al Ain and Babel were involved in a conflict over Babel's disciplinary issues with the club's hierarchy and regarding his use of social media. The club demoted him to the reserves citing poor performance.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/ryan-babel-part-of-al-ain-reserve-team |title=Ryan Babel part of Al Ain 'reserve team' |first=Ashwani |last=Kumar |newspaper=Khaleej Times}}</ref>\n\n===Be\u015fikta\u015f===\nIn January 2017, Babel joined [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] on a two-and-a-half-year deal.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/38492178|title=Ryan Babel: Former Liverpool forward joins Turkish side Besiktas |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2 January 2017 |accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref> Despite only joining the club in January, Babel became a crucial member of the squad that season, making 18 [[2016\u201317 S\u00fcper Lig|league]] appearances and scoring 5 goals as he helped Be\u015fikta\u015f secure their fifteenth league title.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/fall-rise-ryan-babel-how-14464244 |title=The fall and rise of Ryan Babel \u2013 how the former Liverpool man has rescued his career |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |date=27 March 2018 |accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Fulham===\nOn 15 January 2019, Babel signed for Premier League club [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on a contract until the end of the [[2018\u201319 Fulham F.C. season|2018\u201319 season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2019/january/15/ryan-babel-signs-for-fulham |title=Babel signs for Fulham |publisher=Fulham F.C. |date=15 January 2019 |accessdate=16 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Galatasaray===\nIn June 2019, Babel agreed to join [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] on a three-year deal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ryan Babel Galatasaray'da |url=https://www.galatasaray.org/haber/gs-sportif-a-s/ryan-babel-galatasarayda/44354 |language=tr |website=galatasaray.org |date=28 June 2019 |accessdate=28 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Second return to Ajax===\nOn 9 January 2020, it was announced that [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] would loan Babel until the end of the season from [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.ajax.nl/streams/ajax-now/ajax-loans-out-ryan-babel-from-galatasaray-.htm|title=Ajax loans out Ryan Babel from Galatasaray|last=|first=|date=|website=Ajax|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Babel Oranje.jpg|150px|thumb|Babel playing for the Netherlands in August 2007]]\n\nBabel took part in the [[2005 FIFA World Youth Championship]]. Babel scored two goals in four games as the Netherlands reached the quarter-finals. There they were defeated by Nigeria, 10\u20139 in a penalty shoot-out (Babel scored his penalty).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/u20worldcup/netherlands2005/matches/round=91020300/match=91020047/index.html |title=Nigeria 1\u20131 Netherlands |publisher=FIFA |date=25 June 2005 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nLater that season, Babel made his international debut on 26 March 2005, away against [[Romanian national football team|Romania]]. He entered the game as a first-half substitute for [[Arjen Robben]] and went on to score the second goal in a 2\u20130 victory.<ref name=fifa/> The goal made Babel the youngest goalscorer in 68 years for the Netherlands<ref name=fifa/> and the fourth-youngest of all time.<ref name=MARCO/> Babel had been a first team regular with Ajax in 2004\u201305 and finished with seven league goals in 22 appearances.\n\nIn 2006, [[Marco van Basten]] included Babel in the Dutch squad for [[2006 FIFA World Cup]]. Due to a knee injury however,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.contacttheplayers.com/profiles/ryan-babel/253.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100502025215/http://www.contacttheplayers.com/profiles/ryan-babel/253.html |archivedate=2 May 2010 |title=Ryan Babel |publisher=contacttheplayers |accessdate=19 June 2010}}</ref> Babel only featured once, as a second-half substitute for [[Ruud van Nistelrooy]] in the group match against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/archive/worldcup/germany2006/matches/round=97410100/match=97410037/index.html |title=Netherlands 0\u20130 Argentina |publisher=FIFA |date=21 June 2005 |accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> Van Basten has been quoted as saying Babel \"has all the potential to become the next [[Thierry Henry]]\".<ref name=MARCO>{{cite news |url=http://sport.independent.co.uk/football/premiership/article2183792.ece |title=Gunners ready to snare Babel, 'the new Henry' |last=Burt |first=Jason |newspaper=The Independent |date=27 January 2007 |accessdate=7 May 2007 |location=London |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070818061523/http://sport.independent.co.uk/football/premiership/article2183792.ece |archivedate=18 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2007, Babel was part of the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands under-21 team]] competing in the [[2007 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship|UEFA Under-21 Championship]], being held in the Netherlands. In the group stage, Babel scored a penalty against Portugal, helping the Dutch to secure a semi-final spot and thus qualifying for the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in Beijing. His second tournament goal came during his [[man of the match]] performance in the final as the Netherlands defeated [[Serbia national under-21 football team|Serbia]] 4\u20131 to retain their title.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/under21/news/kind=4/newsid=555143.html |title=Babel pays tribute to best vintage |publisher=UEFA |date=25 June 2007 |accessdate=11 July 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629013958/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/under21/news/kind=4/newsid=555143.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=29 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2008, Babel was selected for the Dutch squad which would compete in the [[UEFA Euro 2008]] tournament. On 31 May, it was announced that Babel had been withdrawn from the squad after tearing ankle ligaments in training. Van Basten added then-[[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] defender [[Khalid Boulahrouz]] to his squad in place of Babel.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2008/netherlands/7429356.stm |title=Injury rules Babel out of Euros |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=31 May 2008 |date=2 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n===2010 World Cup===\nBabel was included in the preliminary squad for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] in South Africa.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iO9bETRJh0iovmmUN7ZeFDugTEIg |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219200542/https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iO9bETRJh0iovmmUN7ZeFDugTEIg?hl=en |archivedate=19 December 2013 |title=Van Marwijk trims Dutch squad to 27 |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=15 May 2010 |accessdate=18 May 2010}}</ref> On 27 May 2010, Netherlands manager [[Bert van Marwijk]] announced that the player would be part of the final squad of 23 participating in the competition.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/may/27/holland-world-cup-23-man-squad |title=Holland coach Bert van Marwijk finalises World Cup squad |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 May 2010 |agency=Press Association |accessdate=27 May 2010 |location=London}}</ref> Though the Netherlands reached [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final|the final]], Babel did not appear in any of the matches during the tournament.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n===Euro 2012===\nBabel returned in Oranje after an absence of almost a year on 11 November 2011 as a starter in the pre Euro 2012 0\u20130 drawn friendly against Switzerland.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=1715444.html |title=Netherlands draw blank against Switzerland by Berend Scholten on UEFA.com |publisher=UEFA |date=11 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u2013present===\nOn 29 September 2017, Babel was recalled to the Oranje squad after a six-year absence for the 2018 FIFA World Cup qualifiers against Sweden and Belarus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12021/11059279/ryan-babel-back-in-netherlands-squad-after-six-year-absence|title=Ryan Babel back in Netherlands squad after six-year absence|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> The Netherlands failed to qualify for the tournament; despite this, Babel was regularly called up for the upcoming inaugural [[UEFA Nations League]] campaign. He scored the equaliser in a 2\u20131 away defeat to France<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/36166/11494243/france-2-1-netherlands-kylian-mbappe-and-olivier-giroud-send-world-champions-top-of-group-a1|title=France 2-1 Netherlands: Kylian Mbappe and Olivier Giroud send world champions top of Group A1|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> in the Netherlands' first Nations League match.\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|20 February 2020}}<ref name=\"sw\">{{cite web |title=R. Babel |url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/ryan-babel/43/ |website=Soccerway |accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=espn>{{cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/player/41418/ryan-babel |title=Ryan Babel Player Profile |website=ESPN FC |date=7 May 2007 |accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://voetbalstats.nl/spelernedxi.php?persid=1538 |title=Ryan Babel |accessdate=8 June 2019 |language=Dutch |publisher=voetbalstats.nl}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup<ref group=\"nb\">Includes [[KNVB Cup]], [[Johan Cruyff Shield]], [[FA Cup]], [[DFB-Pokal]], [[Turkish Cup|T\u00fcrkiye Kupas\u0131]], [[Turkish Super Cup|TFF S\u00fcper Kupa]], [[UAE League Cup]] and [[Arabian Gulf Super Cup]].</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[UEFA|Europe]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals||Apps||Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]\n|[[2003\u201304 Eredivisie|2003\u201304]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Eredivisie]]\n|1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|[[2004\u201305 Eredivisie|2004\u201305]]\n|20||7||3||1||4||1||27||9\n|-\n|[[2005\u201306 Eredivisie|2005\u201306]]\n|25||2||4||3||11||2||40||7\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 Eredivisie|2006\u201307]]\n|27||5||5||0||11||3||43||8\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!73!!14!!12!!4!!26!!6!!111!!24\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n|[[2007\u201308 Premier League|2007\u201308]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Premier League]]\n|30||4||6||1||13||5||49||10\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 Premier League|2008\u201309]]\n|27||3||5||0||10||1||42||4\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 Premier League|2009\u201310]]\n|25||4||3||0||10||2||38||6\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Premier League|2010\u201311]]\n|9||1||2||0||6||1||17||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!91!!12!!16!!1!!39!!9!!146!!22\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim]]\n|[[2010\u201311 Bundesliga|2010\u201311]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Bundesliga]]\n|15||1||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||16||1\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Bundesliga|2011\u201312]]\n|31||4||4||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||35||5\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!46!!5!!5!!1!!0!!0!!51!!6\n|-\n|[[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]\n|[[2012\u201313 Eredivisie|2012\u201313]]\n|Eredivisie\n|16||4||2||1||4||0||22||5\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Kas\u0131mpa\u015fa Spor Kul\u00fcb\u00fc|Kas\u0131mpa\u015fa]]\n|[[2013\u201314 S\u00fcper Lig|2013\u201314]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[S\u00fcper Lig]]\n|29||5||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||30||5\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 S\u00fcper Lig|2014\u201315]]\n|29||9||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||29||9\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!58!!14!!1!!0!!0!!0!!59!!14\n|-\n|[[Al Ain FC|Al-Ain]]\n|[[2015\u201316 UAE Pro-League|2015\u201316]]\n|[[UAE Arabian Gulf League]]\n|8||1||6||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||14||2\n|-\n|[[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]]\n|[[2016\u201317 La Liga|2016\u201317]]\n|[[La Liga]]\n|11||4||1||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||12||5\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K. season|2016\u201317]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|S\u00fcper Lig\n|18||5||0||0||6||3||24||8\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K. season|2017\u201318]]\n|32||13||5||0||6||2||43||15\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K. season|2018\u201319]]\n|12||4||0||0||7||2||19||6\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!62!!22!!5!!0!!19!!7!!86!!29\n|-\n|[[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]\n|[[2018\u201319 Fulham F.C. season|2018\u201319]]\n|Premier League\n|16||5||0||0||0||0||16||5\n|-\n|[[Galatasaray S.K.|Galatasaray]]\n|[[2019\u201320 Galatasaray S.K. season|2019\u201320]]\n|S\u00fcper Lig\n|15||5||1||0||4||0||20||5\n|-\n|[[AFC Ajax|Ajax]] (loan)\n|[[2019\u201320 AFC Ajax season|2019\u201320]]\n|Eredivisie\n|4||0||1||1||1||0||6||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career totals\n!400!!86!!50!!10!!93!!22!!543!!118\n|}\n\n<references group=\"nb\" />\n\n=== International ===\n{{updated|10 October 2019.}}<ref name=\"NFT\">{{NFT|11198|accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\