<ref>{{cite book|title=Fatal Frame | type=instruction manual | edition=NTSC, PS2 |publisher=Tecmo |date=2002 | quote=Nine days have passed since Mafuyu, brother of Miku Hinasaki, had disappeaered.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Fatal Frame II: Crimson Butterfly | type=instruction manual | edition=NTSC, PS2 |publisher=Tecmo |date=2003 | quote=Many also say that, if you should happen to get lost in this forest, you will be spirited away to this lost village.}}</ref> by ghosts often leading them into a spirit world where they use the Camera Obscura (\u5c04\u5f71\u6a5f / \u3057\u3083\u3048\u3044\u304d shaeiki), an antique camera-like device that captures images of spirits to either find a way out or save someone who has been spirited away.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brown |first1=Andrew |title=Scary Nintendo Memories: Fatal Frame |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/feature/32312/scary-nintendo-memories-fatal-frame |website=Nintendo World Report |publisher=NINWR, LLC. |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Yama-bito]]\n* [[Tengu]]\n* [[Unexplained disappearances]]\n* [[Mets\u00e4npeitto]]\n* [[\u014ckami Kakushi]]\n\n==References==\n* {{Cite journal | doi = 10.2307/1177730| jstor = 1177730| title = Supernatural Abductions in Japanese Folklore| year = 1967| last1 = Blacker | first1 = C. | journal = Asian Folklore Studies| volume = 26| issue = 2| pages = 111\u2013147}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Staemmler | first1 = Birgit | year = 2005 | title = Virtual Kamikakushi: An Element of Folk Belief in Changing Times and Media | journal = Japanese Journal of Religious Studies | volume =32  | issue = 2 | pages = 341\u2013352 | jstor = 30234067 | url =  | format = }}\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = Sadler | first1 = A. W.  | year = 1987 | title = The Spirit-Captives of Japan's North Country: Nineteenth Century Narratives of the \"Kamikakushi\" | journal = Asian Folklore Studies | volume = 46 | issue = 2 | pages =  217\u2013226 | jstor = 1178585 | doi=10.2307/1178585 | url